We can identify its politics without reference to the SSP. If the SSP disappeared tomorrow, socialists in England, Scotland and Wales would still need to fight for a republican socialist party.}{\b\fs20\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  
\par 
\par }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Never\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
theless the SSP provides important lessons for the working class movement in England. The SSP shows it is possible to build a mass party to the left of the Labour Party. It has united the majority of the socialist movement and provides a genuine challenge
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 to the Scottish Labour Party.}{\fs20\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 The SSP is democratically organised with rights for platforms and tendencies. It is starting to get support from trade unions such as the RMT, CWU and FBU. The Scottish example shows }{\fs20\cf1\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 \hich\f0 that a 
\'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 republican socialist party\'94\loch\f0  is not \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
an abstract theory. It is a feasible and practical answer to the vacuum on the left. If a republican socialist party is possible in Scotland, it is also possible in England and Wales [or for that matter Ireland]. The example of the SSP should help to insp
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 re the struggle for a new party.}{\b\fs20\cf1\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0          
\par 
\par }{\b\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.  The current situation and the urgent need for a republican socialist party 
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid3281690 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Politics in Britain is dominated by a right wing Labour government in alliance with a neo-conservative administration in Washington.\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 Labour is committed to capitalism, the constitutional monarchy and US imperialism. The party is neither republican nor socialist. It articulates the values of liberalism or individual freedom, which translates into the maximum freedom for business and 
\'93\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 \hich\f0 exibility\'94\loch\f0 
 for workers. The Labour government supports a raft of anti-working class policies, from privatising the NHS, and cutting pensions, occupying of Iraq and attacking civil liberties. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The working class movement cannot mount an effective political \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
challenge to the government without its own independent party which puts forward an alternative to capitalism, the constitutional monarchy and US imperialism. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 There is an urgent need for such a party. Lets consider the objective conditions.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i)  The crisi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s of Labourism 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid3281690 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
The traditional forms of working class political representation through the Labour Party and the Communist Party of Great Britain which existed since World War 2 have collapsed. We should not underestimate the importance of the CPGB during
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  this period in organising working class militants and putting pressure on the Labour left. Since the 1990\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s this structure has collapsed. The (old) CPGB was liquidated, the Labour left marginalised and the Labour Party abandoned any pretence of socialism\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
and now occupies the centre-right in British politics. There is a political vacuum on the left.  
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The experience of the Labour government since 1997 has convinced trade union activists that Labour is opposed to their interests. The RMT and FBU are no long\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
er affiliated and other unions are reducing their financial support. We are in a similar position to the end of the 19}{\fs20\super\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 th}{\fs20\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 century when trade unions began to break from the Liberal Party and look for a new working class party to represent working class inter\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ests. The majority of active trade unionists recognise the bankruptcy of New Labour even if it is not clear what to do about it. 
\par 
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid3281690 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ii)  The crisis of democracy and a constitution in flux 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid3281690 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The least recognised aspect of the current situation is the growing\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 crisis of parliamentary democracy. Socialists have long recognised that the constitutional monarchy is not a democratic system of government. In the last ten years the failure of Britain\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s parliamentary democracy has become obvious to a broader section o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 society. The war in Iraq and the anti-war movement served to highlight this problem. Parliament failed to make the Blair government accountable for its illegal war or the manipulation of public opinion. The system concentrates too much power into the han
